derstanding of the act of knowing. Armstrong demonstrates how the novelists' attitudes toward the process of knowing inform experiments with representation, through which they thematize the relation between the understanding of a fictional world and everyday habits of perception. Finally, he considers how these experiments with the strategies of narration produce a heightened awareness of the process of interpretation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnglish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aKnowledge, Theory of, in literature. 0aMimesis in literature. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aWest European History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 20th Century .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501722721?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501722721zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501722721/original  a978-3-11-053617-1 Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA